PUH-BrianMartell Schematic Equation for Dissipation- In PUH v25, dissipation is the slow, irreversible leakage of topological tension from knots (matter) into linear ripples (photons). This provides the microscopic source of the arrow of time. Simple picture:   Knot = localized high-tension twist (stable due to topology).   Small leakage channel: Lattice modes near knot edge allow gradual fraying  tension diffuses as low-amplitude ripples.   Rate proportional to knot surface area (exposure) and tension gradient.   No complete unwind (topology protects bulk)  slow bleed  macroscopic irreversibility. Schematic equation (dimensionless form): \frac{\mathrm{d}E_{\text{knot}}}{\mathrm{d}t} = -\gamma , S , \Delta T   E_knot = stored tension energy   S = effective surface exposure   T = tension gradient at boundary    = small dimensionless leakage constant (lattice coupling) This ensures slow, local entropy increase while conserving total energy (ripples carry it away).
